                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1490">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.41/107a.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to Consul
                            <persName type="to">Letcher</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-02-28T13:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 28, 1914, 1 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>British Ambassador communicated on February 21 a telegram from Mrs. Benton
                    praying that her husband’s body be recovered before decomposition sets in.</p>
                <p>Unofficially inform Villa that the failure to deliver body is being made the
                    basis of speculation and bitter criticism. Request that he give immediate orders
                    that body be delivered up to relatives or to Collector of the Port of El
                    Paso.</p>
                <p>Act quickly and telegraph result.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bryan</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
